item.label: Cerebral lobe, Occipital
item.name: Cerebral lobes Occipital
item.description: The occipital lobe is the most posterior lobe of the cerebral hemispheres. It is clinically important because it includes the primary and association visual cortex.

item.label: Cerebral fissure, Calcarine
item.name: Cerebral fissure Calcarine
item.description: The calcarine fissure or sulcus is AKA as Area 17 of Brodmann. It is a prominent sulcus on the medial surface of the occipital lobe consisting of an upper bank (cuneus) and lower bank (lingual gyrus) where the neurons of the primary visual cortex are located.

item.label: Visual pathway, Line of Gennari
item.name: Visual pathway Line of Gennari
item.description: The Line of Gennari is AKA the Stripe of Gennari.  It is a thin, white stripe in the primary visual cortex of the calcarine cortex. Visual cortex is often called striate cortex because of this line that is visible to the naked eye.

item.label: Medulla
item.name: Medulla
item.description: The medulla is AKA the medulla oblongata. The most caudal aspect of the brain stem, it is located between the pons and spinal cord. It contains structures vital to survival such as cardiovascular and respiratory centers, as well as many cranial nerve nuclei. The major ascending and descending tracts travel through it between the spinal cord and higher centers. It originates developmentally from the myelencephalon of the hindbrain.

item.label: Gracile fasciculus
item.name: Gracile fasciculi
item.description: The gracile fasciculus is part of the dorsal or posterior column of white matter along the entire length of the spinal cord. It includes large, uncrossed, primary afferent fibers carrying tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive input from the lower extremity and the body below approximately T6.  While most of these fibers will terminate in the gracile nuclei in the caudal medulla, a substantial portion will terminate in Clark's nucleus (nucleus dorsalis) in the lumbar and lower thoracic aspect of the spinal cord.  Note that in upper thoracic and cervical cord segments, the dorsal column includes a more laterally located fiber bundle, the cuneate fasciculus.  The fibers in the cuneate fasciculus carry the same modalities of sensation from the upper extremity and the body above approximately T6.

item.label: Gracile nucleus
item.name: Gracile nuclei
item.description: The gracile nucleus contains the second-order neurons that receive tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive input from the lower body and lower extremity via the gracile fasciculus of the spinal cord. The axons of these gracile neurons decussate in the medulla to form the medial lemniscus which will travel to and synapse in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Cuneate fasciculus
item.name: Cuneate fasciculi
item.description: The cuneate fasciculus is the lateral portion of the dorsal or posterior column rostral to T6. It includes large, uncrossed, primary afferent fibers carrying tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive input from the upper extremity and the body above approximately T6; most of these fibers will terminate in the cuneate and lateral cuneate nuclei in the medulla.

item.label: Cuneate nucleus
item.name: Cuneate nuclei
item.description: The cuneate nucleus contains the second-order neurons that receive tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive input from the upper extremity and the body above T6 via the cuneate fasciculus of the spinal cord. The axons of these cuneate neurons decussate in the medulla to form the medial lemniscus which will travel to and synapse in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Spinal trigeminal nucleus
item.name: Spinal trigeminal nuclei
item.description: The trigeminal spinal nucleus is AKA the spinal trigeminal nucleus. It is a portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei that exists as a longitudinal column of cells within the lateral aspect of the caudal pons and medulla. Caudally, it merges with the dorsal horn of the spinal cord (particularly, the substantia gelatinosa); rostrally it merges into the trigeminal main sensory nucleus. It consists of second-order sensory neurons that receive primarily pain and temperature information from the head via input from the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract. Efferents from this nucleus terminate in the contralateral ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Hemisphere
item.name: Hemispheres
item.description: The cerebellar hemispheres are the largest portion of the cerebellum located on either side of the midline vermis. They are functionally important relative to coordination of the limbs.

item.label: Vermis
item.name: Vermis
item.description: The vermis of the cerebellum is the most medial region, i.e. the narrow midline section associated with the anterior, posterior and flocculonodular lobes of the cerebellum.

item.label: Cortex
item.name: Cortex
item.description: The outer cortical surface of the cerebellum is folded into fine-caliber ridges called folia.  This cortex consists of three layers, an outer molecular layer, an inner granular layer and a Purkinje cell layer in the middle at the junction of the molecular and granular layers.

item.label: Medullary Center
item.name: Medullary Center
item.description: The medullary center of the cerebellum is the white matter in the center of the cerebellum.  It is composed of the nerve fibers traveling to and from the cerebellar cortex and deep cerebellar nuclei.

item.label: Cerebellum, Deep nuclei
item.name: Cerebellum, deep nuclei
item.description: The deep nuclei of the cerebellum (dentate, globus, emboliform and fastigial nuclei) are located within the white matter core of the cerebellum. While they receive afferent input from extra-cerebellar sources, their main input is from the Purkinje cells of the cerebellar cortex. Their output constitutes the primary output of the cerebellum, per se, and travels primarily in the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the motor part of thalamus plus in the red nuclei.

item.label: Dentate
item.name: Dentate
item.description: The dentate nucleus is the largest and most lateral of the deep cerebellar nuclei. It appears as a highly-convoluted draw-string purse with a small opening or hilus from which its efferent fibers exit on their way to the superior cerebellar peduncle. Afferents to the dentate nucleus are primarily from the neocerbellar cortex or lateral aspects of the hemispheres. Efferents terminate primarily in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus. Because of a similar shape, it can be confused with the inferior olivary nucleus found in the medulla.

item.label: Emboliform
item.name: Emboliform
item.description: The emboliform nucleus is one of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum located medial to the dentate nucleus and lateral to the globose nucleus. In non-human species it is combined with the globose nucleus as a single nuclear mass and called the 'interposed' nucleus or 'nucleus interpositus'; this term is commonly used in human neuroanatomy as well. It receives input from the paravermal zone of cerebellar cortex and projects its output via the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus and the red nucleus.

item.label: Globose
item.name: Globose
item.description: The globose nucleus is one of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum located between the fastigial and emboliform nuclei. In non-human species it is combined with the emboliform nucleus as a single nuclear mass and called the 'interposed' nucleus or 'nucleus interpositus'; this term is commonly used in human neuroanatomy as well. It receives input from the paravermal zone of cerebellar cortex and projects its output via the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus and the red nucleus.

item.label: Fastigial
item.name: Fastigial
item.description: The fastigial nucleus is the most medially located of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum. Its primary input is from the vermis of the cerebellum and it projects its output bilaterally to the vestibular nuclei and reticular formation. Through these brainstem connections, the cerebellum can influence lower motor neurons via the vestibulospinal and reticulospinal tracts.

item.label: Lateral ventricle, Posterior horn
item.name: Ventricular system Lat vent,post horn
item.description: The lateral ventricle is a large, C-shaped space within each cerebral hemisphere that is filled with cerebrospinal fluid. It consists of an anterior (or frontal) horn that extends into the frontal lobe, a body, a posterior (or occipital) horn that extends into the occipital lobe, an inferior (or temporal) horn that extends into the temporal lobe and the atrium or trigone where the body, posterior limb and inferior limb meet.
